    "created_at": "2017-08-09T14:52:15Z",
    "updated_at": "2017-08-09T14:52:15Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "@jskeet I think writing to a console by default is a reasonable default behavior and it seems to make first steps with gRPC easier - as a new user, I'd prefer the application to tell me about issues with my setup (e.g. failure to connect to a server, dns resolution problem and others that seem pretty common when trying to run your gRPC application for the application) rather than staying silent and me needing to discover somewhat hidden logging options to actually see some useful info to debug.\r\nThe reverse process seems much more straightforward: I have an application -> it prints stuff that I don't like -> I look for gRPC Logging configuration -> I easily discover the setting and use GrpcEnvironment.SetLogger(NullLogger()) to silence the logs.\r\n\r\nA bit more philosophically, it depends if one perceives gRPC as a library (logging by default might be questionable) or as a framework (in which case logging to the console seems reasonable - all application servers I know about do that)."
  },
